# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: admission-to-the-union
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] With the initial meeting of the First Congress, the United States federal government officially began operations under the new (and current) frame of government established by the 1787 Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the provisions of Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, of the Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Pro-Administration majority.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] There were no political parties in this Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Members are informally grouped into factions of similar interest, based on an analysis of their voting record.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Details on changes are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for North Carolina and Rhode Island when each ratified the Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] During this congress, five House seats were added for North Carolina and one House seat was added for Rhode Island when they ratified the Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are listed by their districts.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island were the last states to ratify the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Constitution and, due to their late ratification, were unable to send full representation at the beginning of this Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Six Senators and nine Representatives were subsequently seated from these states during the sessions as noted.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] There was 1 resignation, 1 death, 1 replacement of a temporary appointee, and 6 new seats.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] The Anti-Administration Senators picked up 1 new seat and the Pro-Administration Senators picked up 5 new seats.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] There was 2 resignations, 1 death, and 6 new seats.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Anti-Administration members picked up 3 seats and Pro-Administration members picked up 2 seats.
[src:admission-to-the-union/1st-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] "**51st state**" is a phrase used in the United States to refer to the idea of adding an additional state to the current 50-state nation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Proposals for a 51st state may include granting statehood to one of the U.S. territories or Washington, D.C., splitting an existing state, or annexing part or all of a sovereign country.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The U.S. has not admitted any new states to the union since 1959, when both Alaska (on January 3) and Hawaii (on August 21) were admitted.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Before that, no states had been admitted since Arizona in February 1912.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Before Alaska and Hawaii became U.S. states, the equivalent expression was "the 49th state".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] For example, the National Movement for the Establishment of a 49th State was a 1930s movement that sought to create a primarily Black state in the Southern United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In the 2010s, and the 2020s, the term has been used most often in reference to active statehood movements in Washington, D.C., and in Puerto Rico, both voted for statehood in recent referendums: D.C. in 2016 and Puerto Rico in 2020.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Their admission to the Union as states would require congressional approval.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The two regions have different statuses within the U.S., with Puerto Rico as one of the five permanently inhabited U.S. territories, while D.C. has unique status as a federal administrative district.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The path to statehood for Puerto Rico in particular would have parallels to the admission process of most U.S. states outside of the original Thirteen British Colonies, which started as territories before becoming states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Since the 2024 U.S. presidential election, the phrase has also been frequently invoked in reference to Canada, as Donald Trump has used the phrase repeatedly while calling for the U.S. annexation of Canada.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The U.S. annexed sovereign nations as states in the past, including Texas, Hawaii, and Vermont, though this has not happened in recent history.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Some U.S. states have experienced movements to split into two states, often due to strong political disagreements between different regions of a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] There is precedent for such state-splitting moves in U.S. history, such as the creation of Kentucky and West Virginia from Virginia, though, again, there have been no such moves in more than a century.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The phrase can also be used as a slang term in reference to regions or sovereign nations around the world that are not actually considered prospects for U.S. annexation, but are considered to be aligned with U.S. culture or political or military interests.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This slang may be used in either a positive sense, or in a pejorative sense (particularly towards Canada), similar to the term Americanization.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Article IV, Section 3, Clause 1 of the United States Constitution authorizes Congress to admit new states into the United States (beyond the 13 already in existence at the time the Constitution went into effect in 1788).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Historically, most new states brought into being by Congress have been established from an organized incorporated territory, created and governed by Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In some cases, an entire territory became a state; in others, some part of a territory became a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Although not a legal rule, historically having at least 60,000 free adult males was also a requirement for statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This was outlined in the Northwest Ordinance decreed in 1787 when the United States was under the Articles of Confederation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Even though the United States no longer operates under this government, Congress has generally followed this guideline as states were added to the union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In most cases, the organized government of a territory made known the sentiment of its population in favor of statehood, usually by referendum.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress then directed that government to organize a constitutional convention to write a state constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Upon acceptance of that constitution by the people of the territory and then by Congress, a joint resolution would be adopted granting statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The President would then issue a proclamation adding a new state to the Union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] While Congress, which has ultimate authority over the admission of new states, has usually followed this procedure, there have been occasions (because of unique, case-specific circumstances) when it did not.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A simple majority in each House of Congress is required to pass statehood legislation; however, in the United States Senate, the filibuster requires 60 votes to invoke cloture.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Some statehood advocacy organizations have called for amending or abolishing the filibuster as a path to achieve statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] As with other legislation, the President can sign or veto statehood bills that pass, and Congress has the power to override a veto with a two-thirds majority; Nebraska is the only existing state admitted through a veto override.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Although Congress, with approval of the President, can add a state to the Union, they cannot make another State by splitting or merging two existing states, without the consent of the State (or States) legislatures involved.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] While states can join the United States, the 1869 Supreme Court case *Texas v.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] White* established that once they do so it is illegal to leave.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This was a point of contention during the Civil War.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] If a new U.S. state were to be admitted, it would require a new design of the flag to accommodate an additional star for the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Army Institute of Heraldry, an existing United States flag never becomes obsolete.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In the event that a new state is added to the Union and a 51-star flag is approved, any previously approved American flag (such as the 48-star flag or 50-star flag) may continue to be used and displayed until no longer serviceable.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Mayor Muriel Bowser ordered flags with 51 stars to be hung along Pennsylvania Avenue in support of D.C. being added as a 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Should a 51st state be admitted, it would receive U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Senate seats in classes 1 and 2, at which point all three classes would have 34 senators.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The District of Columbia is often mentioned as a candidate for statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 43 of *The Federalist Papers*, James Madison considered the implications of the definition of the "seat of government" found in the United States Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Although he noted potential conflicts of interest, and the need for a "municipal legislature for local purposes", Madison did not address the district's role in national voting.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The District of Columbia residents who support the statehood movement sometimes use the slogan "Taxation without representation" to denote their lack of Congressional representation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The phrase is a shortened version of the Revolutionary War protest motto "no taxation without representation" omitting the initial "No", and is printed on newly issued District of Columbia license plates (although a driver may choose to have the District of Columbia website address instead).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] President Bill Clinton's presidential limousine had the "Taxation without representation" license plate late in his term, while President George W.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Bush had the vehicle's plates changed shortly after beginning his term in office.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] President Barack Obama had the license plates changed back to the protest style shortly before his second-term inauguration.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] President Donald Trump eventually removed the license plate and signaled opposition to D.C. statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Statehood Party, a political party; it has since merged with the local Green Party affiliate to form the D.C.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The nearest this movement ever came to success was in 1978, when Congress passed the District of Columbia Voting Rights Amendment.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Two years later in 1980, local citizens passed an initiative written and filed by J.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Edward Guinan calling for a constitutional convention for a new state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In 1982, voters ratified the constitution of the state, which was to be called New Columbia.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The drive for statehood stalled in 1985, however, when the District of Columbia Voting Rights Amendment failed because not enough states ratified the amendment within the allowed seven-year span.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This would give residents of the District of Columbia the benefit of statehood while precluding the creation of a 51st state, but would require the consent of the Government of Maryland.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On April 15, 2016, District Mayor Muriel Bowser called for a citywide vote on whether the nation's capital should become the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This was followed by the release of a proposed State Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This Constitution would make the Mayor of the District of Columbia the Governor of the proposed state, while the members of the District Council would make up the proposed House of Delegates.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On November 8, 2016, the voters of the District of Columbia voted overwhelmingly in favor of statehood, with 86% of voters voting to advise approving the proposal.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] While the name "New Columbia" has long been associated with the movement, the City Council and community members chose the proposed state name to be the State of Columbia, or the State of Washington, Douglass Commonwealth.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Maryland abolitionist Frederick Douglass was a D.C. resident and was chosen to be the proposed state's namesake alongside George Washington of Virginia.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This would ensure federal control of federal buildings.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The National Mall, the White House, the national memorials, Cabinet buildings, judicial buildings, legislative buildings, and other government-related buildings, etc. would be housed within the much smaller federal seat of government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] All residences in the State of Washington, D.C. would reside outside the seat of federal government, except for the White House.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The proposed boundaries are based on precedents created through the 1902 McMillan Plan with a few modifications.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The rest of the boundaries would remain the same.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On June 26, 2020, the United States House of Representatives voted 232–180 in favor of statehood for Washington, D.C.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Passage of this legislation in the Senate was unlikely while the Republican Party held a Senate majority, and President Donald Trump also promised to veto D.C. statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 51, was in honor of D.C. potentially becoming the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] After the 2020 Senate elections, the Democratic Party had a Senate majority, meaning Joe Biden's presidency might have opened the door for D.C. statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The vote was the first time D.C. ever had a vote for statehood pass any chamber of Congress: in 1993, D.C. statehood legislation was rejected in a US House floor vote by 153–277.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Another problem is that because Maryland released the land to become D.C., it may have a claim on any land released by Congress to become a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On April 22, 2021, the United States House of Representatives voted 216–208 in favor of statehood for Washington, D.C.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 51, "A bill to provide for the admission of the State of Washington, D.C. into the Union" was earlier introduced into the United States Senate.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On April 30, Democratic senator Joe Manchin came out against both bills, effectively dooming their passage.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] (See 117th United States Congress) Senator Manchin said the way to make D.C. a State was by a constitutional amendment, which was the process for the voting rights with the 23rd Amendment.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] He went further, stating that the complications created by shrinking the Federal District to the National Mall with the 23rd Amendment should be addressed.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] While others disagreed, he thought that if had been approved it would end up in the Supreme Court.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Rico has been discussed as a potential 51st state of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 1965 – Puerto Rico Admission Act, 5% of the lower legislature were in support.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The bill was passed on to the House Committee on Natural Resources.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In a 2012 status referendum a majority of voters, 54%, expressed dissatisfaction with the existing political relationship.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In a separate question, 61% of voters supported statehood (excluding the 26% of voters who left this question blank).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On December 11, 2012, Puerto Rico's legislature resolved to request that the President and the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress act on the results, end its territorial status and begin the process of admitting Puerto Rico to the Union as a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On January 4, 2017, Puerto Rico's new representative to Congress pushed a bill that would ratify statehood by 2025.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On June 11, 2017, another non-binding referendum was held where 97.7 percent voted for the statehood option.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The turnout for this vote was 23 percent, a historical low as voter turnout in Puerto Rico usually hovers around 80%.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The low turnout was attributed to a boycott led by the pro-status quo PPD party.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On June 27, 2018, the Puerto Rico Admission Act of 2018 H.R.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The admission act had 37 original cosponsors among Republicans and Democrats in the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A subsequent nonbinding referendum was held on November 3, 2020, to decide whether Puerto Rico should become a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 8393 (the Puerto Rico Status Act) passed the House of Representatives in a 233–191 vote with 11 absences.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] It would have instituted a binding referendum that would allow Puerto Ricans to vote on the future status of the island, that Congress would be required to obey.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Every Democrat voted in favor of the bill, and was joined by 16 Republicans.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The 2024 Puerto Rican status referendum was also a win for Statehood in the November 2024 election, which also saw a Pro-Statehood Governor of Puerto Rico elected.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Since 1898, Puerto Rico has had limited representation in the United States Congress in the form of a Resident Commissioner, a non-voting delegate.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The 110th Congress returned the Commissioner's power to vote in the Committee of the Whole, but not on matters where the vote would represent a decisive participation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Rico has elections on the United States presidential primary or caucus of the Democratic Party and the Republican Party to select delegates to the respective parties' national conventions although presidential electors are not granted on the Electoral College.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] As American citizens, Puerto Ricans can vote in U.S. presidential elections, provided they reside in one of the 50 states or the District of Columbia and not in Puerto Rico itself.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Residents of Puerto Rico pay U.S. federal taxes: import and export taxes, federal commodity taxes, social security taxes, thereby contributing to the American Government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Most Puerto Rico residents do not pay federal income tax but do pay federal payroll taxes (Social Security and Medicare).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] However, federal employees who do business with the federal government, Puerto Rico–based corporations that intend to send funds to the U.S., and others do pay federal income taxes.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Ricans may enlist in the U.S. military.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Ricans have participated in all American wars since 1898; 52 Puerto Ricans had been killed in the Iraq War and War in Afghanistan by November 2012.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Rico has been under U.S. sovereignty for over a century after it was ceded to the U.S. by Spain following the end of the Spanish–American War, and Puerto Ricans have been U.S. citizens since 1917.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The island's ultimate status has not been determined, and its residents do not have voting representation in their federal government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Like the states, Puerto Rico has self-rule, a republican form of government organized pursuant to a constitution adopted by its people, and a bill of rights.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This constitution was created when the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress directed local government to organize a constitutional convention to write the Puerto Rico Constitution in 1951.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The acceptance of that constitution by Puerto Rico's electorate, the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress, and the U.S. president occurred in 1952.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In addition, the rights, privileges and immunities attendant to United States citizens are "respected in Puerto Rico to the same extent as though Puerto Rico were a State of the Union" through the express extension of the Privileges and Immunities Clause of the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Puerto Rico is designated in its constitution as the "Commonwealth of Puerto Rico".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Constitution of Puerto Rico, which became effective in 1952, adopted the name of *Estado Libre Asociado* (literally translated as "Free Associated State"), officially translated into English as Commonwealth, for its body politic.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The island is under the jurisdiction of the Territorial Clause of the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Constitution, which has led to doubts about the finality of the Commonwealth status for Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In addition, all people born in Puerto Rico become citizens of the U.S. at birth (under provisions of the Jones–Shafroth Act in 1917), but citizens residing in Puerto Rico cannot vote for the President of the United States nor for full members of either house of Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Statehood would grant island residents full voting rights at the federal level and 2 state senators, like each US state has.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Bush issued a Memorandum to heads of Executive Departments and Agencies establishing the administrative relationship between the Federal Government and the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This memorandum directs all Federal departments, agencies, and officials to treat Puerto Rico administratively as if it were a State insofar as doing so would not disrupt Federal programs or operations.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] President Bush's memorandum remains in effect until Federal legislation is enacted to alter the status of Puerto Rico in accordance with the freely expressed wishes of the people of Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On April 29, 2010, the United States House of Representatives approved the Puerto Rico Democracy Act (H.R.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 2499) by 223–169, but was not approved by the Senate before the end of the 111th Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] It would have provided for a federally sanctioned self-determination process for the people of Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This act would provide for referendums to be held in Puerto Rico to determine the island's ultimate political status.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] It had previously been introduced in 2007.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In November 2012, a referendum resulted in 54 percent of respondents voting to reject its status under the territorial clause of the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Constitution, while a second question resulted in 61 percent of voters identifying statehood as the preferred alternative to its territorial status.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The 2012 referendum was by far the most successful referendum for statehood advocates and support for statehood rose in each successive popular referendum.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] However, more than one in four voters abstained from answering the question on the preferred alternative status.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Statehood opponents have argued that the statehood option garnered 45 percent of the votes if abstentions are included.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] If abstentions are considered, the result of the referendum is much closer to 44 percent for statehood, a number that falls under the 50 percent majority mark.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Several days after the referendum, the Resident Commissioner Pedro Pierluisi, Governor Luis Fortuño, and Governor-elect Alejandro García Padilla wrote separate letters to the President of the United States, Barack Obama, addressing the results of the voting.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Pierluisi urged Obama to begin legislation in favor of the statehood of Puerto Rico, in light of its win in the referendum.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Fortuño urged him to move the process forward.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] García Padilla asked him to reject the results because of their ambiguity.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The White House position on the November 2012 plebiscite was that the results were clear, the people of Puerto Rico want the issue of status resolved, and a majority chose statehood in the second question.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On May 15, 2013, Resident Commissioner Pierluisi introduced H.R.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 2000 to Congress to "set forth the process for Puerto Rico to be admitted as a state of the Union", asking for Congress to vote on ratifying Puerto Rico as the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On February 12, 2014, Senator Martin Heinrich introduced a bill in the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The bill would require a binding referendum to be held in Puerto Rico asking whether the territory wants to be admitted as a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In the event of a yes vote, the president would be asked to submit legislation to Congress to admit Puerto Rico as a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] On January 15, 2014, the United States House of Representatives approved $2.5 million in funding to hold a referendum.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This referendum can be held at any time as there is no deadline by which the funds have to be used.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The United States Senate then passed the bill which was signed into law on January 17, 2014, by Barack Obama, then President of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The previous plebiscites had provided voters with three options: statehood, free association, and independence.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Puerto Rican status referendum of 2017 instead originally offered two options: statehood and independence/free association; however, a third option, "current territorial status" was later added.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The referendum was held on June 11, 2017, with an overwhelming majority of voters supporting statehood at 97.16%; however, with a voter turnout of 22.99%, it was a historical low.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The specifics of the association agreement would have been to be detailed in the Compact of Free Association that would have had to be negotiated between the U.S. and Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] That document could have covered topics such as the role of the U.S. military in Puerto Rico, the use of the U.S. currency, free trade between the two entities, and whether Puerto Ricans would be U.S. citizens.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The governor, Ricardo Rosselló was strongly in favor of statehood to help develop the economy and help to "solve our 500-year-old colonial dilemma ...
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] 3.5 million citizens seeking an absolute democracy".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Benefits of statehood would include an additional $10 billion per year in federal funds, the right to vote in presidential elections, higher Social Security and Medicare benefits, and the right for its government agencies and municipalities to file for bankruptcy.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] At approximately the same time as the referendum, Puerto Rico's legislators were expected to vote on a bill that would allow the Governor to draft a state constitution and hold elections to choose senators and representatives to the United States Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Regardless of the outcome of the referendum or the bill on drafting a constitution, action by Congress would have still been necessary to implement changes to the status of Puerto Rico under the Territorial Clause of the United States Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] If the majority of Puerto Ricans were to choose the Free Association option – and 33% voted for it in 2012 – and if it were granted by the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress, Puerto Rico would become a Free Associated State, a virtually independent nation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] It would have a political and economical treaty of association with the U.S. that would stipulate all delegated agreements.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This could give Puerto Rico a similar status to Micronesia, the Marshall Islands, and Palau, countries which have a Compact of Free Association with the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Those Free Associated States use the American dollar, receive some financial support and the promise of military defense if they refuse military access to any other country.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Their citizens are allowed to work in the U.S. and serve in its military.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In total, 500,000 Puerto Ricans voted for statehood, 7,600 voted for independence, and 6,700 voted for status quo.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A referendum of the status of Puerto Rico was held on November 3, 2020, concurrently with the general election.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This was the sixth referendum held on the status of Puerto Rico, with the previous one having taken place in 2017.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] This was the first referendum with a simple yes-or-no question, with voters having the option of voting for or against becoming a U.S. state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The referendum was non-binding, as the power to grant statehood lies with the US Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The party platforms of both the Republican Party and the Democratic Party have affirmed for decades Puerto Rico's right to self-determination and to be admitted as a state, at least in theory, but individual Republican legislators have been more skeptical.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] According to Senate Bill 1467, which placed the referendum on the ballot, voting "No" on the referendum would mean that a seven-member commission would be appointed to negotiate with the federal government for the free association or independence of Puerto Rico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In 2024 another referendum was conducted, with three choices: Statehood, Independence, or Independence with Free Association.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Statehood won with 58% of the vote in this referendum, though it did not include an option for status quo.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Guam (formally the Territory of Guam) is an unincorporated and organized territory of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Located in the western Pacific Ocean, Guam is one of five American territories with a civilian government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Northern Marianas in later referendums chose to join the United States, which it did in 1986 as the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, but like Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands has not reached statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In the 1980s and early 1990s, there was a significant movement in favor of Guam becoming a commonwealth, which would give it a level of self-government similar to Puerto Rico and the Northern Mariana Islands.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] However, the federal government rejected the version of commonwealth that the government of Guam proposed, because its clauses were incompatible with the Territorial Clause (Art.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Other movements advocate U.S. statehood for Guam, union with the state of Hawaii, union with the Northern Mariana Islands as a single territory, or independence.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In a 1982 plebiscite, voters indicated interest in seeking commonwealth status.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The island has been considering another non-binding plebiscite on decolonization since 1998.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Governor Eddie Baza Calvo intended to include one during the island's November 2016 elections but it was delayed again.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A Commission on Decolonization was established in 1997 to educate the people of Guam about the various political status options in its relationship with the U.S.: statehood, free association and independence.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In 2013, the commission began seeking funding to start a public education campaign.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] There were few subsequent developments until late 2016.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In early December 2016, the Commission scheduled a series of education sessions in various villages about the status of Guam's relationship with the U.S. and the self-determination options that might be considered.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The commission's executive director is Edward Alvarez and there are ten members.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The group is also expected to release position papers on independence and statehood but they have not yet been completed.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Guam was occupied for over 450 years by the Spanish and then the Japanese.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Under the United States the people have had several referendums to determine their fate, and the current status dates to 1980s referendum which was won to continue as territory of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Several late 20th referendums also determined they did not desire a unification with the Northern Marianas to the north, which joined the United States as territory in 1986.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In 2016, Governor Eddie Calvo planned a decolonization referendum solely for the indigenous Chamorro people of Guam, in which the three options would be statehood, independence, and free association.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] However, this referendum for the Chamorro people was struck down by a federal judge on the grounds of racial discrimination.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] In the wake of this ruling, Governor Calvo suggested that two ballots be held: one for the Chamorro People and one for eligible U.S. citizens who are non-indigenous residents of Guam.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A reunification referendum in Guam and its neighbor, the Northern Mariana Islands (a U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A 2016 poll conducted by the University of Guam showed a majority supporting statehood when respondents were asked which political status they supported.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The United Nations is in favor of greater self-determination for Guam, though it has concluded its interest in the Northern Marianas which was removed from list of non self governing after it chose to join in the United States after a series of referendums in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The UN's Special Committee on Decolonization has agreed to endorse the governor's education plan.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The commission's May 2016 report stated: "With academics from the University of Guam, [the Commission] was working to create and approve educational materials.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Office of the Governor was collaborating closely with the Commission" in developing educational materials for the public.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The United States Department of the Interior had approved a $300,000 grant for decolonization education, Edward Alvarez told the United Nations Pacific Regional Seminar in May 2016.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Indian Territory attempted statehood in 1905, when citizens of the Five Civilized Tribes proposed creating the State of Sequoyah as a means to retain control of their lands and resources.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] A constitutional convention was held on August 21, 1905, in Muskogee, and the proposed constitution was overwhelmingly approved by the territory's indigenous and white residents.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Congress did not support statehood for Sequoyah, and the Indian Territory was annexed into Oklahoma in 1907.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Virgin Islands explored the possibility of statehood in 1984 and in a 1993 referendum, while American Samoa explored the possibility of statehood in 2005 and 2017.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The United States annexed the Philippines as its territory from the Spanish Empire in 1898 and established the Insular Government of the Philippine Islands in 1901.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Since then, the Philippines has had small grassroots movements for U.S. statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Originally part of the platform of the Progressive Party, then known as the Federalista Party, the party dropped it in 1907, which coincided with the name change.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Philippines became an independent nation in 1946.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] During the Philippine presidential elections of 1981, 4% of the electorate voted for Bartolome Cabangbang, a member of the Interim Batasang Pambansa from Bohol.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] He ran under the Federal Party which advocated for a plebiscite to convert the Philippines into the 51st US state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] As recently as 2004, the concept of the Philippines becoming a U.S. state has been part of a political platform in the Philippines.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Supporters of this movement include Filipinos who believe that the quality of life in the Philippines would be higher and that there would be less poverty there if the Philippines were an American state or territory.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Supporters also include Filipinos that had fought as members of the United States Armed Forces in various wars during the Commonwealth period.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] The Philippine statehood movement had a significant impact during its early period as an American territory.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] It is no longer a mainstream movement, but it is still a social movement that periodically gains interest and talk in the nation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] No major politician in the Philippines has advocated for US statehood as of 2014.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Election candidates in favor of the proposal have been declared as "nuisance candidates" by the Philippine government's election commission.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] There have historically been several proposals, with varying degrees of support, to divide states having regions that are politically or culturally divergent into smaller, more homogeneous, administratively efficient entities.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p01] Splitting a state requires the approval of both its legislature and the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Some countries, because of their cultural similarities and close alliances with the United States, or American egotism are sometimes described as a 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In other countries around the world, movements with various degrees of support and seriousness have proposed U.S. statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In Canada, "the 51st state" is a phrase generally used to imply that if a certain political course is taken, Canada's destiny will be little more than a part of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The phrase is usually used in local political debates, in polemic writing or in private conversations.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] It is rarely used by politicians in public, although at certain times in Canadian history political parties have used other similarly loaded imagery.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Within days, however, the PCs responded with an ad which featured the border being drawn back *on* with a permanent marker.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The implication has historical basis and dates to the breakup of British America during the American Revolution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The first invasion occurred in 1775–1776 mainly across the Canadian side of the Lake Champlain and St.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] That invasion's failure forced the members of those regiments into exile, and they settled mostly in upstate New York.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] However, the Continental Army was more successful in the Western theater in lands north of the Ohio Valley and south of the Great Lakes region, both of which were part of Canada.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Articles of Confederation, written during the Revolution, included a provision for Canada to join the United States, should they ever decide to do so, without needing to seek U.S. permission as other states would.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] What is now Prince Edward Island (then Saint John's Island) was successfully captured by Continental militias, but George Washington ordered the island's return, stating that he wanted colonies to join willingly, not be forcibly captured.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] At the end of the Revolution, the U.S. took portions of Canadian territory of what is now present day Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, Wisconsin, and parts of Minnesota in accordance to the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The U.S. again invaded Canada during the War of 1812, but this effort was made more difficult due to the wide use of ill-equipped state militias and owing to the large number of Loyalists that had fled to what is now Ontario and still resisted joining the republic.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Hunter Patriots in the 1830s and the Fenian raids after the American Civil War were private attacks on Canada from the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Several U.S. politicians in the 19th century also spoke in favor of annexing Canada, as did Canadian politician William Lyon Mackenzie, who set up a rogue Republic of Canada on a small island near the U.S. border during the Upper Canada Rebellion.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In the United States, the term "the 51st state" when applied to Canada is used disparagingly, intended to deride Canada as an inconsequential neighbor.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In December 2024, then-President-elect Donald Trump suggested Canada consider becoming the 51st U.S. state, during talks with then-Prime Minister Justin Trudeau over proposed tariffs and border security at Mar-a-Lago.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] He later referred to Trudeau as "Governor Justin Trudeau of the Great State of Canada".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] This was initially taken as a joke, with Ontario Premier Doug Ford joking on Fox News that this was Trump's attempt at revenge for the War of 1812.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Trump continued to refer to Trudeau as "Governor", even after he resigned from office, and repeatedly declared his desire for Canadian annexation throughout his first 100 days in office, including while proposing major tariffs on the Canadian economy.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] He quipped that NHL legend Wayne Gretzky should run to become the Governor of an annexed Canada.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Trump's comments reignited pre-existing discourse on U.S.-Canadian union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Canadian author Don Tapscott was among those who considered the logistics of a full merger, in which Canada would need to be composed of 13 states or territories.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Since Donald Trump's comments on his support of annexing Canada, there have been a number of opinion polls conducted asking Canadians on their opinion of the proposal.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The responses from Canadians have been overwhelmingly against Canada joining the United States as the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Some polls have also been conducted asking American opinions on Canada being annexed as the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] An Angus Reid poll reported 49% of Americans opposing the proposal and 25% supporting it, with 26% being unsure.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The name was a contraction of "best union." The party soon folded.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] One example of a Canadian annexation movement is in the province of Alberta.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In the 21st century, an Alberta51 separatist project was founded and gained some media attention.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Peter Zeihan argued in his book *The Accidental Superpower* that the Canadian province of Alberta would benefit from joining the United States as the 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] There is growing support for Alberta separatism resulting from federal government policies which are believed to be harming the province's ability to build pipelines for the province's oil and gas industry and federal equalization payments.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In a September 2018 poll, 25% of Albertans believed they would be better off separating from Canada and 62% believed they are not getting enough from confederation.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Ever since Trump's proposal on annexing Canada in 2024, interest within the Albertan annexationist movement has drawn increased attention within Alberta's political landscape.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 2025, the Republican Party of Alberta was formed modeled after the US American Republican Party.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The movement ultimately failed when, in a 1948 referendum, voters narrowly chose to confederate with Canada (the Economic Union Party supported an independent "responsible government" that they would then push toward their goals).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In the 1989 Quebec general election, the political party Parti 51 ran 11 candidates on a platform of Quebec seceding from Canada to join the United States (with its leader, André Perron, claiming Quebec could not survive as an independent nation).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The party attracted just 3,846 votes across the province, 0.11% of the total votes cast.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In comparison, the principal party in favor of Quebec sovereignty in that election, the Parti Québécois, got 40.16%.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1847–1848, with the United States' resounding defeat of Mexico and the occupying at the conclusion of the Mexican–American War, there was talk in Congress of annexing the entirety of Mexico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The result was the Mexican Cession through the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo, named for the town in which the treaty was signed, in which the U.S. annexed almost 31% of Mexico.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Mexican Cession consisted of territory that became the states of California, Nevada, Utah, most of Arizona, the western half of New Mexico, the western quarter of Colorado, and the southwest corner of Wyoming.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Later in 1854, the United States made the Gadsden Purchase official.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1848, a bill was debated in Congress that would have annexed the Republic of Yucatán, but there was no vote.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] However, the U.S. never acted on these proposals from some U.S. politicians; some of which were never delivered or considered seriously.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 2001, El Salvador adopted the U.S. dollar as its currency, while Panama has used it for decades due to its ties to the Canal Zone.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1854, the Ostend Manifesto outlined a rationale for the U.S. to purchase Cuba from Spain, implying that it might take the island by force if Spain refused.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Once the document was published, many Northern states denounced it.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1859, Senator John Slidell introduced a bill to purchase Cuba from Spain.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Cuba, like many Spanish territories, wanted to break free from Spain.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] A pro-independence movement in Cuba was supported by the U.S., and Cuban guerrilla leaders wanted annexation to the United States, but Cuban revolutionary leader José Martí called for Cuban nationhood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] When the U.S. battleship *Maine* sank in Havana Harbor, the U.S. blamed Spain and the Spanish–American War broke out in 1898.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] After the U.S. won, Spain relinquished its claim of sovereignty over most of its remaining territories, including Cuba.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The U.S. administered Cuba as a protectorate until 1902.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1898, one news outlet in the Caribbean noted growing sentiments of resentment of British rule in Dominica, including its system of administration.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The publication attempted to gauge sentiments concerning annexation to the United States as a way to change this system of administration.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] On June 30, 1870, the United States Senate voted against an annexation treaty with the Dominican Republic.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] During World War II, when Denmark was occupied by Nazi Germany, the United States briefly controlled Greenland for battlefields and protection, since the nation was in a strategic position.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1946, the United States offered to buy Greenland from Denmark for US$100,000,000 (US$1,600,000,000 as of 2024) but Denmark refused to sell.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Some have, in recent years, argued that Greenland would hypothetically be better off financially as part of the United States; for instance this was mentioned by Professor Gudmundur Alfredsson at the University of Akureyri, Iceland, in 2014.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Trump administration in both administrations have both expressed interest in Greenland, as per American expansionist policies.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] One possible reason for U.S. interest in Greenland is its vast natural resources.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] According to The Arctic Institute, the U.S. appears to be highly interested in investing in the resources of the island and in tapping the expected vast amount of hydrocarbons off the Greenlandic coast, as well as for national defence on the development of a missile defence system for the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] , with the red-white-blue color scheme of the U.S. flag.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In Guyana, there is a fringe group named "Guyana, USA", which seeks for the incorporation of the country into the United States, whether as a new state or territory.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Albania has been called the 51st state for its perceived strongly pro-American positions, and the United States' policies towards it.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Bush's 2007 European tour, Edi Rama, Tirana's mayor and leader of the opposition Socialists, said: "Albania is for sure the most pro-American country in Europe, maybe even in the world ...
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Nowhere else can you find such respect and hospitality for the President of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Even in Michigan, he wouldn't be as welcome." At the time of ex-Secretary of State James Baker's visit in 1992, there was a move to hold a referendum declaring the country as the 51st American state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Kosovo (which is predominately Albanian) has been considered as a 51st state due to the heavy presence and influence of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The U.S. has had troops and the largest base outside U.S. territory, Camp Bondsteel, in the territory since 1999.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1873, the leader of the Canton of Cartagena, Roque Barcia, requested that Cartagena become part of the United States in a letter to President Ulysses S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Canton of Cartagena had emerged in the same year as a revolt against the First Spanish Republic.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The United States Government never replied.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 1989, the *Los Angeles Times* published that Denmark becomes the 51st state every Fourth of July, because Danish citizens in and around Aalborg celebrate the American Independence Day in a small gathering called the Rebild Festival.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Poland has historically been staunchly pro-American, dating to General Tadeusz Kościuszko and Casimir Pulaski's support of the American Revolution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] This pro-American stance was reinforced following favorable American intervention in World War I (leading to the creation of an independent Poland) and the Cold War (culminating in a Polish state independent of Soviet influence).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Poland contributed a large force to the "Coalition of the Willing" in Iraq.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] A quote referring to Poland as "the 51st state" has been attributed to James Pavitt, then Central Intelligence Agency Deputy Director for Operations, especially in connection to extraordinary rendition.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Currently, Poland ranks as the nation with the most favorable view of the United States among countries surveyed internationally, with more than 85% of Poles expressing positive views toward America as of 2024.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The Italian Unionist Movement was a political party briefly active during and after World War II, with the goal of an annexation of Italy to the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In Sicily, the Party of Reconstruction was one of several Sicilian nationalist and separatist movements active after the downfall of Italian Fascism.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Sicilians felt neglected or underrepresented by the Italian government after the annexation of 1861 that ended the rule of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies based in Naples.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] It claimed 40,000 members in 1944, and campaigned for Sicily to be admitted as a U.S. state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The United Kingdom has sometimes been called "the 51st state" due to the Special Relationship in United Kingdom–United States relations, particularly since the close cooperation between Franklin D.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Roosevelt and Winston Churchill during World War II, and more recently during the premierships of Margaret Thatcher and Tony Blair.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In the 1960s, prior to the accession of the United Kingdom to the European Economic Community (as it was then), Prime Minister Harold Wilson reportedly held informal discussions with US President Lyndon Johnson about the possibility of the UK becoming America's 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In an April 5, 1999 article in *Forbes*, historian Paul Johnson proposed that, as an alternative to the European Union, the UK should become ten states (one each for Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales, with England divided into seven).
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] He went on to suggest that then Canada (as one state per province), Australia, and New Zealand should also join this expanded United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In a 2011 column in *The Times*, journalist David Aaronovitch joked that the UK should consider joining the United States as its 51st state, because Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom and Brexit would otherwise lead to terminal decline.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] He also made an alternative case that England, Scotland, and Wales should be three separate states, with Northern Ireland joining the Republic of Ireland and becoming an all-Ireland state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The UK band New Model Army released the song "51st State" in 1986.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The lyrics facetiously refer to the "Star Spangled Union Jack" and describes the UK as culturally and politically dominated by the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In Australia, the term '51st state' is used to disparage the perceived invasion of American cultural or political influence.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] In 2010, there was an attempt to register a *51st State Party* with the New Zealand Electoral Commission.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The party advocates New Zealand becoming the 51st state of the United States of America.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The party's secretary is Paulus Telfer, a former Christchurch mayoral candidate.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] On February 5, 2010, the party applied to register a logo with the Electoral Commission.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The logo – a U.S. flag with 51 stars – was rejected by the Electoral Commission on the grounds that it was likely to cause confusion or mislead electors.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] All these trusteeships were slowly returned to Japanese rule.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Okinawa was returned on May 15, 1972, but the U.S. stations troops in the island's bases as a defense for Japan.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The continued military presence has been described as a 51st state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Several sources assert that Israel functions as a 51st state due to the annual funding, defense and overall support it receives from the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] An example of this is the 2003 book by Martine Rothblatt called *Two Stars for Peace* that argued for the addition of Israel and Palestine as the 51st and 52nd states of the Union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] *The American State of Canaan* is a book by political scientist and sociologist Alfred de Grazia from March 2009, proposing the creation of the "State of Canaan" from Israel and Palestine.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] According to Iran's former IRGC Commander-in-Chief Salami, before the 1979 Iranian revolution, Iran was practically the 51st state of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Several publications suggested that the 2003 invasion of Iraq was a neocolonialist war to make Iraq into the 51st U.S. state, though such statements are usually made facetiously.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] A group called Taiwan Civil Government, established in Taipei in 2008, claims that the island of Taiwan and other minor islands are a territory of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The idea of admission to the United States was discussed among some netizens based on Hong Kong's mature common law system, long tradition of liberalism and vibrant civil society making it a global financial hub similar to London or New York.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] There are no African countries historically tied to the United States more closely than Liberia.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Established by the American Colonization Society in 1822 as a home for freed Black Americans, Liberia's capital, Monrovia, was named after James Monroe, the fifth U.S. president.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Liberia has sometimes been regarded as a "mini-America" on the West African coast because its people speak English, use U.S. customary units, have modeled the flag after the Stars and Stripes and even created a U.S.-style constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Many Liberians regard the U.S. as their "mother country".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] "We are the 51st state," said Herbert Walker, a Liberian street merchant.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] "We sang your national anthem and learned American history.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] During the 2025 Honduran general election, the presidential candidate Mario "Chano" Riveras (Christian Democratic Party) has proposed to annex Honduras to United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The motto of his campaign is "Join the gringos".
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The remark was widely interpreted as a reference to the recent capture of Nicolás Maduro by United States forces earlier that year.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The following day, after Venezuela defeated the United States in the championship game, Trump again posted on Truth Social, writing simply “Statehood,” in apparent reference to the same idea.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] On 12 May of the same year, Trump posted an image on his official Truth Social account depicting a map of Venezuela filled with the flag of the United States and the caption “51st State”.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Minutes later, the official White House account on X published a video featuring U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] Secretary of State Marco Rubio paraphrasing rapper The Notorious B.I.G. with the phrase “If you don’t know, now you know”, while his music played in the background following the announcement of the capture of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:admission-to-the-union/51st-state-p02] The video then showed the widely circulated image of Maduro aboard an aircraft en route to New York after his capture, before ending with Rubio wearing the same grey Nike tracksuit Maduro had worn at the time of his arrest.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film depicts events surrounding creation of the United States Constitution, and is focused mainly on James Madison, who wrote most of that document and took extensive notes during the convention's discussions and proceedings.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] The period immediately following the American Revolutionary War was marked by intense political unrest, owing to huge debts, the interruption of trade and business, shortages of labor, and personal turmoils, all created by the War.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] It soon became evident that the Articles of Confederation were insufficient to address the country's needs.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] A movement soon emerged to upgrade or replace the Articles, and Madison was foremost in the movement.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] However, he needed the support of George Washington, and needed to show that a new government would be sufficient to address such challenges as Shays' Rebellion and the growing trade problems between the independent States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was strongly opposed by those who feared a strong central government, people known either as *States Rights Advocates* or as *Anti-Federalists*, such as Roger Sherman and John Dickinson.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was in favor of a bicameral congress, and envisioned each house being elected with seats allocated to states in proportion to population.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] In this he was opposed by the States Rights Advocates, and he eventually accepted the compromises necessary to address their concerns.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film highlights the basis for these compromises.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film also depicts the convention delegates' debate about the slave trade.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] The movie was filmed on location at Independence Hall in Philadelphia, in Williamsburg, Virginia, and at other historical sites.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] Much of the film is shot from the viewpoint of James Madison, with the script being based primarily on his writings.
[src:admission-to-the-union/a-more-perfect-union-film] These include the copious minutes he took during the Constitutional Convention, which were published after his death as *Notes of Debates in the Federal Convention of 1787*.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin served as a United States Senator from Georgia from 1799 to 1807.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] During his tenure, he served as President pro tempore of the United States Senate from 1801 to 1802.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Abraham Baldwin was born in 1754 in Guilford in the Connecticut Colony into a large family, the son of Lucy (Dudley) and Michael Baldwin, a blacksmith, and descended from Elder John Strong.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] His half-brother, Henry Baldwin, was an Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] After attending Guilford Grammar School, Abraham Baldwin attended Yale College in nearby New Haven, Connecticut, where he was a member of the Linonian Society.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Three years later after theological study, he was licensed as a Congregationalist minister.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He also served as a tutor at the college.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] During the American Revolutionary War, he served as a chaplain in the Connecticut Contingent of the Continental Army.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He did not see combat while with the Continental troops.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Two years later at the conclusion of the war, Baldwin declined an offer from Yale's new president, Ezra Stiles, to become Professor of Divinity.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Instead, he turned to the study of law and in 1783 was admitted to the Connecticut bar.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Encouraged by his former commanding officer General Nathanael Greene, who had acquired the plantation at Mulberry Grove where Eli Whitney would later invent the cotton gin, Baldwin moved to Georgia.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He was recruited by fellow Yale alumnus Governor Lyman Hall, another transplanted New Englander, to develop a state education plan.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin was named the first president of the University of Georgia and became active in politics to build support for the university, which had not yet enrolled its first student.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He was appointed as a delegate to the Congress of the Confederation and then to the Constitutional Convention; in September 1786 he was one of the state’s two signatories to the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin remained president of the University of Georgia during its initial development phase until 1800.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] During this period, he also worked with the legislature on the college charter.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] In 1801, Franklin College, the University of Georgia's initial college, opened to students.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Josiah Meigs was hired to succeed Baldwin as first acting president and oversee the inaugural class of students.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] The first buildings of the college were architecturally modeled on Baldwin's and Meigs's *alma mater* of Yale where they both had taught.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin was elected to the Georgia Assembly, where he became very active, working to develop support for the college.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He was able to mediate between the rougher frontiersmen, perhaps because of his childhood as the son of a blacksmith, and the aristocratic planter elite who dominated the coastal Lowcountry.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He became one of the most prominent legislators, pushing significant measures such as the education bill through the sometimes split Georgia Assembly.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He was elected as representative to the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] The Georgia legislature elected him as U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] Senator in 1799 (this was the practice until popular election in 1913).
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He served as president pro tempore of the United States Senate from December 1801 to December 1802.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] He was re-elected and served in office until his death.
[src:admission-to-the-union/abraham-baldwin] On March 4, 1807, at age 52, Baldwin died while serving as a U.S. senator from Georgia.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] In the United States, an **act of Congress** is a statute passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives of the United States Congress and signed into law by the president.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Acts may apply only to individual entities (called private laws), or to the general public (public laws).
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] In the United States, acts of Congress are designated as either **public laws**, relating to the general public, or **private laws**, relating to specific institutions or individuals.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Since 1957, all acts of Congress have been designated as "Public Law X–Y" or "Private Law X–Y".
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] X is the number of the Congress and Y refers to the sequential order of the bill (when it was enacted).
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] 111–5 (American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009) was the fifth enacted public law of the 111th United States Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Public laws are also often abbreviated as Pub.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] When the legislation of those two kinds are proposed, it is called public bill and private bill respectively.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The word "act", as used in the term "act of Congress", is a common, not a proper noun.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The capitalization of the word "act" (especially when used standing alone to refer to an act mentioned earlier by its full name) is deprecated by some dictionaries and usage authorities.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] However, the Bluebook requires "Act" to be capitalized when referring to a specific legislative act.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The United States Code capitalizes "act".
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The term "act of Congress" is sometimes used in informal speech to indicate something for which getting permission is burdensome.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Reconsideration by the Congress after a presidential veto during its session.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] A bill must receive a 2⁄3 majority vote in both houses to override a president's veto.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The president promulgates acts of Congress made by the first two methods.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] If an act is made by the third method, the presiding officer of the house that last reconsidered the act promulgates it.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Under the United States Constitution, if the president does not return a bill or resolution to Congress with objections before the time limit expires, then the bill automatically becomes an act.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] If the Congress is adjourned at the end of this period, then the bill dies and cannot be reconsidered (see pocket veto).
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] If the president rejects a bill or resolution while the Congress is in session, a two-thirds vote of both houses of Congress is needed for reconsideration to be successful.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Promulgation in the sense of publishing and proclaiming the law is accomplished by the president, or the relevant presiding officer in the case of an overridden veto, delivering the act to the archivist of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] The archivist provides for its publication as a slip law and in the United States Statutes at Large after receiving the act.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Thereafter, the changes are published in the United States Code.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] Through the process of judicial review, an act of Congress that violates the Constitution may be declared unconstitutional by the courts.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] A judicial declaration that an act of Congress is unconstitutional does not remove the act from the Statutes at Large or the United States Code; rather, it prevents the act from being enforced.
[src:admission-to-the-union/act-of-congress] However, the act as published in annotated codes and legal databases is marked with annotations indicating that it is no longer good law.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Of the 37 states admitted to the Union by Congress, all but six have been established within existing U.S. organized incorporated territories.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] A state that was so created might encompass all or part of a territory.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The use of an enabling act has been a common historic practice, but several states were admitted to the Union without one.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] In many instances, an enabling act would detail the mechanism by which the territory would be admitted as a state after the ratification of their constitution and the election of state officers.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Although the use of such an act is a traditional historic practice, several territories have drafted constitutions for submission to Congress absent an enabling act but were subsequently admitted.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The broad outline for the process was established by the Land Ordinance of 1784 and the 1787 Northwest Ordinance, both of which predate the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The Admission to the Union Clause forbids the creation of new states from parts of existing states without the consent of all of the affected states and that of Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The primary intent of the caveat was to give the four Eastern States that still had western land claims (Connecticut, Georgia, North Carolina, and Virginia) a veto over whether their western counties could become states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The clause has since served the same function each time that a proposal to partition an existing state or states has arisen.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Between 1781 and 1789, the United States was governed by a unicameral Congress, the Congress of the Confederation, which operated under authority granted to it by the Articles of Confederation, the nation's first constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The 11th Article authorized Congress to admit new states to the Union provided nine states consented.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Under the Articles, each state cast one vote on each proposed measure in Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] During this period, the Confederation Congress enacted two ordinances governing the admission of new states into the Union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The first such ordinance was the Land Ordinance of 1784, enacted April 23, 1784.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Thomas Jefferson was its principal author.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The ordinance called for the land (recently confirmed as part of the United States by the Treaty of Paris) west of the Appalachian Mountains, north of the Ohio River and east of the Mississippi River to eventually be divided into ten states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Once a given area reached 20,000 inhabitants, it could call a constitutional convention and form a provisional government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Then, upon enacting a state constitution which affirmed that the new state would forever be part of the Confederation, it would be admitted on an equal footing with all other states, based on a majority vote in Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The 1784 ordinance was superseded three years later by the Northwest Ordinance of 1787.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Enacted by the Confederation Congress on July 13, 1787, it created the Northwest Territory, the first organized incorporated territory of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] No new states were formed in the Northwest Territory under either ordinance.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] In 1789, the 1st United States Congress reaffirmed the Northwest Ordinance with slight modifications.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The Northwest Territory remained in existence until 1803, when the southeastern portion of it was admitted to the Union as the State of Ohio, and the remainder was reorganized.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] At the 1787 Constitutional Convention, a proposal to include the phrase "new States shall be admitted on the same terms with the original States" in the *new states* clause was defeated.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] That proposal would have taken the policy articulated in the Ordinance of 1784 and made it a constitutional imperative.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Many delegates objected to including the phrase, fearing that the political power of future new western states would ultimately overwhelm that of the established eastern states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Delegates, understanding that the number of states would inevitably increase, did agree to include wording into this clause to preclude formation of a new state out of an established one without the consent of the established state as well as the Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] It was anticipated that Kentucky (which was a part of Virginia), Franklin (which was a part of North Carolina, and later became part of the Southwest Territory), Vermont (to which New York asserted a disputed claim), and Maine (which was a part of Massachusetts), would become states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] As a result of this compromise, new breakaway states are permitted to join the Union but only with the proper consents.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Shortly after the new Constitution went into effect Congress admitted Vermont and Kentucky on equal terms with the existing 13 states and thereafter formalized the condition in its acts of admission for subsequent states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Thus the Congress, utilizing the discretion allowed by the framers, adopted a policy of equal status for all newly admitted states.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The constitutional principle derived from these actions is known as the equal footing doctrine.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] With the growth of states' rights advocacy during the antebellum period, the Supreme Court asserted, in *Lessee of Pollard v.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Hagan* (1845), that the Constitution mandated admission of new states on the basis of equality.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Historically, most new states formed by Congress have been established from an organized incorporated U.S. territory, created and governed by Congress in accord with its plenary power under Article IV, Section 3, Clause 2 of the Constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] In some cases, an entire territory became a state; in others some part of a territory became a state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Congress then empowered that government to organize a constitutional convention to write a state constitution.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Upon acceptance of that constitution, by the people of the territory and then by Congress, Congress would adopt by simple majority vote a joint resolution granting statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Then the President of the United States would sign the resolution and issue a proclamation announcing that a new state had been added to the Union.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] While Congress, which has ultimate authority over the admission of new states, has usually followed this procedure, there have been occasions when it did not.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Congress is under no obligation to admit states, even in those areas whose population expresses a desire for statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] In one instance, Mormon pioneers in Salt Lake City sought to establish the state of Deseret in 1849.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] It existed for slightly over two years and was never approved by the Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] In 1905, leaders of the Five Civilized Tribes (Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Seminole) in Indian Territory proposed to establish the state of Sequoyah as a means to retain control of their lands.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The proposed constitution ultimately failed in Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Instead, the Indian Territory was incorporated into the new state of Oklahoma in 1907.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Some U.S. territories existed only a short time before becoming states, while others remained territories for decades.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The shortest-lived was Alabama Territory at 2 years, while New Mexico and Hawaii territories both were in existence for more than 50 years.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The entry of several states into the Union has been delayed by complicating factors.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Among them, Michigan Territory, which petitioned Congress for statehood in 1835, was not admitted to the Union until 1837, because of a boundary dispute with the adjacent state of Ohio.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] The independent Republic of Texas requested annexation to the United States in 1837, but fears about potential conflict with Mexico delayed the admission of Texas for nine years.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Also, statehood for Kansas Territory was held up for several years (1854–1861) because of a series of internal violent conflicts involving anti-slavery and pro-slavery factions.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] Once established, most state borders have, with few exceptions, been generally stable.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] There have been numerous minor adjustments to state boundaries over the years as a result of improved surveys, resolution of ambiguous or disputed boundary definitions, or minor mutually agreed boundary adjustments for administrative convenience or other purposes.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] One notable example is the case *New Jersey v.
[src:admission-to-the-union/admission-to-the-union] New York*, in which New Jersey won roughly 90% of Ellis Island from New York in 1998.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] The **Territory of Alabama** (sometimes **Alabama Territory**) was an organized incorporated territory of the United States.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] The Alabama Territory was carved from the Mississippi Territory on August 15, 1817 and lasted until December 14, 1819, when it was admitted to the Union as the twenty-second state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] The Alabama Territory[n] was designated by two interdependent Acts of the Congress of the United States, passed by both chambers, the Senate and the House of Representatives on March 1 and 3, 1817, but it did not become effective until October 10, 1817.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] The delay was due to a provision in the Congressional Organic Act passed in Washington, which stated that the act would only take effect if and when the western part of the Mississippi Territory (1798–1817) were to form a state constitution and government on the road to statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] Stephens, located in the central area of the Alabama Territory on the Tombigbee River, was the only territorial capital during the period.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] William Wyatt Bibb (1781–1820), formerly of Georgia was the only territorial governor, later elected to that position after achieving statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] On December 14, 1819, Alabama was admitted to the federal Union as the 22nd state, with appointed territorial governor William W.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alabama-territory] Bibb (1781-1820), formerly of Georgia, becoming the elected first state governor (1819–1820).
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] 339, enacted July 7, 1958) was a legislative act introduced by Delegate E.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] "Bob" Bartlett and signed by President Dwight D.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Through it, Alaska became the 49th U.S. state on January 3, 1959.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The law was the culmination of a multi-decade effort by many prominent Alaskans, including Bartlett, Ernest Gruening, Bill Egan, Bob Atwood, and Ted Stevens.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The law was first introduced by James Wickersham in 1916, shortly after the First Organic Act.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] However, due to a lack of interest from Alaskans, the bill was never introduced.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Efforts increased in 1943, with Bartlett's rendition of the act being introduced first in 1947 and 1950, with the backing of President Harry Truman.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] However, due to opposition from powerful southern U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Congressmen, it took until 1958 to pass the law, with the convincing of Bob Bartlett.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Gruening worked on rallying support from Alaskans, launching the Alaska Constitutional Convention in 1956, which elected Bill Egan and Gruening as Shadow U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Senators, and Ralph Rivers as the Shadow U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Representative, working towards pressuring the U.S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Atwood similarly rallied support by using his job as a trusted news source to rally Alaskans for statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Stevens also authored parts of the Act (namely Section 10).
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Roger Ernst, Seaton's former Assistant Secretary for Public Land Management, said of Stevens: "He did all the work on statehood; he wrote 90 percent of all the speeches.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] From 1867 to 1884, Alaska was considered to be a military district of the United States under the control of the federal government, known as the Department of Alaska.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] From 1884 to 1912, it was organized as the District of Alaska, and from 1912 to 1959, it was organized into the incorporated Territory of Alaska.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans had sought statehood since as early as the 1920s, though this vision was not realized until the decade after World War II.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Furthermore, during the 1896–1910 gold rush eras (mainly in the Klondike, Nome, and Fairbanks regions), hundreds of thousands of people traveled to Alaska in search of gold.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Several industries flourished as a result, such as fishing, trapping, mining, and mineral production.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Alaska's resources were depleted to the extent that it came to be considered a "colonial economy".
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] However, Alaska was still considered a district, and local governments often had little control over local affairs.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Several issues arose that made it more difficult for Alaska to push toward self-government.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] One of these was the formation of the "Alaska Syndicate" in 1906 by the two industry barons J.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Their influence spread, and they came to control the Kennecott copper mine, steamship and railroad companies, and salmon packing.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The influence of the Syndicate in Washington D.C. opposed any further movement towards Alaskan home rule.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] James Wickersham, however, grew increasingly concerned over the exploitation of Alaska for personal and corporate interests and took it upon himself to fight for Alaskan self-rule.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] He used the Ballinger–Pinchot affair in order to help achieve this.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] As a result of the affair, Alaska was in the national headlines, and President William Howard Taft was forced to send a message to Congress on February 2, 1912, insisting that they listen to Wickersham.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In August 1912 Congress passed the Second Organic Act, which established the Territory of Alaska with a capital at Juneau and an elected legislature.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The federal government still retained much of the control over laws regarding fishing, gaming, and natural resources and the governor was also still appointed by the President.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In 1916, Wickersham, who was now a delegate to Congress, proposed the first bill for Alaska's statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The bill, however, failed, partly due to lack of interest among Alaskans in gaining statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Discrimination against the Alaskan Territory made it difficult for Congress to get much done.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Discussion of revising the Second Organic Act took up much time but came to no avail.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Instead, Congress passed the Jones Act (also known as the Merchant Marine Act of 1920) and the White Act of 1924 both of which made the fishing problem worse for Alaskans rather than better.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans were angered by these two acts and felt they were discriminatory.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Matters were made worse by regional conflicts which drew attention away from the issue of statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In the 1930s, Alaska was plagued by the Great Depression.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Roosevelt did two significant things for Alaska.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] First, he allowed for 1,000 selected farmers hurt by the depression to move to Alaska and colonize the Matanuska-Susitna Valley, being given a second chance at agricultural success.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Second (and sometimes considered to be more importantly), Roosevelt appointed Ernest Gruening as governor of Alaska in 1939.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Edward Lewis "Bob" Bartlett, who was one of Alaska's territorial delegates to Congress from 1944 to 1958 when he became a U.S. senator representing Alaska, would become one of Gruening's most important allies in supporting the cause for Alaskan statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Alaska's desire for statehood was much aided by the amount of attention it received during World War II.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] After Japan initiated the Aleutian Islands Campaign in June 1942, the territory became an important strategic military base and a key to the Pacific during the war, with a resulting population increase due to the number of American servicemen sent there.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] It remained critically important in deterring Soviet aggression through the Bering Strait during the Cold War.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] However, many barriers still stood between Alaska and statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Many Alaskans, like the Lomen brothers of Nome and Austin E.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] "Cap" Lathrop, who benefited largely from Alaska's small tax base, did not want themselves or their businesses to be hurt financially by the increase in taxes that would result from statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Other Alaskans feared that statehood would result in a flood of more people coming to Alaska, which they didn't want.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] There was enough of a majority, though, that did want statehood so as to be able to pass a referendum for statehood in Alaska in 1946 by a 3:2 vote.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] With the help of the referendum, Bartlett was able to introduce a bill to Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The bill, however, was immediately shot down by a coalition of Democrats and Republicans.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Republicans feared that Alaska would be unable to raise enough taxes due to its small population and end up as a welfare state while Southern Democrats feared more pro-civil rights congressmen.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In retaliation, Gruening established the "Alaska Statehood Committee" in 1949.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] He encouraged journalists, newspaper editors, politicians, and members of national and labor organizations to help use their positions and power to make the issue of Alaskan statehood more known.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] He gathered a group of 100 prominent figures, including Eleanor Roosevelt, actor James Cagney, writers Pearl S.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Buck and John Gunther, historian Arthur M.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Schlesinger Jr., and theologian Reinhold Niebuhr, who all stood for the Alaskan cause.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Another bill was introduced to Congress in 1949 and passed in the House by a 186 to 146 vote in 1950.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] However, the bill was then shot down in the Senate, again for fear of adding more Democrats to the 81st Congress (1949–1951), as the Democrats already had 54 seats to 42 Republican seats.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] On February 27, 1952, the Senate by a one-vote margin (45–44) killed the statehood bill for another year, with Southern Democrats having threatened a filibuster to delay consideration.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In the 1954 State of the Union address, Eisenhower referred to statehood for Hawaii (then a Republican-leaning territory) but not Alaska (then a Democratic-leaning territory).
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] By March, frustrated by Eisenhower's refusal to support statehood for Alaska, a Senate coalition led by Democrats tied the fates of Alaska and Hawaii statehood together as one package.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The procedural move was backed by some Southern Democrats, concerned about the addition of new votes in the civil rights for blacks movement, in the hope of defeating both measures.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Six members of the Senate Interior and Insular Affairs Committee, including Senator Butler, went to Alaska in order to hold public hearings and see for themselves what the public sentiment was in Alaska.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In response to the visit, Alaskans would not let Americans forget the cause.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Citizens sent Christmas cards reading "Make [Alaskans'] future bright/Ask your Senator for statehood/And start the New Year right." Women made bouquets of Alaska's flower, the Forget-Me-Not and sent them to members of Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Movements such as "Operation Statehood" also put increasing pressure on Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] "Lack of public interest" could no longer be used as a feasible excuse to prevent statehood.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Frank Heintzleman proposed that Alaska be divided at the 156th meridian west.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In interest of the growing fervor and enthusiasm toward the cause, a Constitutional Convention was held at the University of Alaska, Fairbanks, in 1955.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] During this convention, Gruening gave a very powerful speech which compared Alaska's situation to the American struggle for independence.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The famous speech was entitled "Let Us End American Colonialism" and had a very influential impact.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The convention was highly praised and very emotional.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The Constitution for Alaska was written up and Alaskans voted and passed the Alaska Constitution in 1956 with overwhelming approval.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The Constitution was named "one of the best, if not the best, state constitutions ever written" by the National Municipal League.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Another step forward for the cause was taken by the Alaskan adoption of the "Tennessee Plan" which allowed them to elect their delegates to Congress without having to wait for an official act from Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans therefore elected to Congress Senators Ernest Gruening and William A.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Egan and Representative to the House Ralph J.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Gruening, Egan, and Rivers attended Congress and were politely received, though they were not officially seated or recognized in any way.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The Alaskan delegation did not give up, however, and worked hard with Bartlett to pressure the Congress into action.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Eventually, with the help of Bartlett's influence, the Speaker of the House, Sam Rayburn, who until 1957 had been an ardent opponent of the Alaskan statehood cause, changed his mind and when Congress reconvened in January 1958, President Eisenhower fully endorsed the bill for the first time.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Johnson promised his commitment to the bill but others still stood in the way, such as Representative Howard W.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Smith of Virginia, Chairman of the powerful Rules Committee, and Thomas Pelly of Washington State who wanted the Alaskan waters to be open to use by Washingtonians.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Senator Prescott Bush of Connecticut stated that Alaska's population was too small, the territory was non-contiguous, economic conditions were unstable and statehood would increase taxes sharply, which would thus disrupt economic development within the state.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Representative Barratt O'Hara attacked the opposition's fear of the act, stating "During my life-time, 10 states have been admitted to the Union and each time opponents raised the arguments of fear and distrust that we have heard in this debate." Representative W.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Debate lasted for hours within both chambers.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Eventually, though, the resistance was able to be bypassed, and the House passed the statehood bill by a 210–166 vote.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] The Senate, which had had its own version of the bill as well as the House's version, finally managed to pass the House's bill through the fervent urging of Bartlett by a 64–20 vote.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] On January 3, 1959, after much struggle and through the efforts of many, Alaska finally became the 49th state of the United States of America after President Eisenhower signed the official declaration.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] All three propositions were approved by Alaskans in a special election held on August 26, 1958.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] On the first question, "Shall Alaska immediately be admitted into the Union as a state?", the result was 40,452 in favor, and 8,010 against.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] In the late 1950s civil rights bills were being introduced in Congress.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] To overcome the Southern Democrats' suppression of the pro-Republican African-American vote, then-Republican Hawaii's prospects for statehood were tied to Alaska's, which many thought would be more Democratic.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] Hawaii statehood was expected to result in the addition of two pro-civil-rights senators from a state which would be the first to have a majority non-white population.
[src:admission-to-the-union/alaska-statehood-act] This would endanger the Southern minority segregationist Democratic Senate by providing two more pro-civil rights votes to invoke cloture and halt a Senate filibuster.
